<section xml:id="section-q1-medium">
  <title>Medium Dataset</title>

  <paragraphs xml:id="Q1-medium">
    <title>Question 1 - Medium Dataset</title>
    
    <p>
      You arrive just before planting. The air is dry and hot, and farmers are already gathering in the shade. One of the farmers spots you, and comes running over.
    </p>
        <image source="images/aminou_question.png" width="70%">
          <description>A farmer approaching Aminou after hearing about the study results, seeking evidence-based advice on which variety to plant</description>
        </image>
    <p>
      <q>Aminou! Thank goodness you're here. I've heard about your study and everyone says you now have real evidence. So tell me - what variety should I plant?</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      You pause. Across Ilam, Regin, and Anikrub, thousands of plots were studied. Farmers tried two varieties: ICRI and Locale.
    </p>

    <p>
      You have the data and so you sit down with them to give them some advice. What do you say?
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Choose your answer:</alert>
      <ul>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-locale">Locale</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-icri">ICRI</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-either">Either</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-idk">I don't know</xref></p></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs xml:id="Q1-medium-locale">
    <title>Locale - Medium Dataset</title>
    
    <p>
      You nod confidently, <q>Plant Locale.</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      The farmer squints at you, <q>Hmm.</q> They're not convinced, and that plays on your mind.
    </p>

    <p>
      Later that evening, as you sit reviewing the data more carefully, something unsettles you.
    </p>

    <p>
      <q>Wait<ellipsis/> what?</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      You flip back through your tables.
    </p>

    <p>
      You would have expected that pattern somewhere else -- but do you expect that here in Ilam?
    </p>

    <p>
      The farmer comes back the next day.
    </p>

    <p>
      <q>So<ellipsis/> are you sure?</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      What do you say now?
    </p>

    <p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-locale-locale">Locale</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-icri-correct">ICRI</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-locale-either">Either</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-locale-idk">I don't know</xref></p></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs xml:id="Q1-medium-locale-locale">
    <title>Locale Again - Medium Dataset</title>
    
    <p>
      You double down, <q>Still Locale.</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      The farmer raises an eyebrow, <q>Do you work for this Locale variety or something?</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      You feel your face warm. That Ilam sun is hot today.
    </p>

    <p>
      Time to slow down.
    </p>

    <assemblage>
      <p>
        Hint: Have you looked at yield by region and variety?
      </p>
      <p>
        Not just overall yield - but yield broken down by region as well as variety.
      </p>
      <p>
        The data are not flat, they are layered. Try again.
      </p>
    </assemblage>

    <p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-help">Locale</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-icri-correct">ICRI</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-help">Either</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-help">I don't know</xref></p></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs xml:id="Q1-medium-locale-either">
    <title>Either - Medium Dataset (After Locale)</title>
    
    <p>
      <q>Either one should be fine.</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      The farmer frowns, <q>That doesn't sound very confident.</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      The Ilam sun is hot and you start to sweat. You realise you may be smoothing over something important.
    </p>

    <assemblage>
      <p>
        Hint: Look at yield by region and variety. Averages across countries can hide regional differences.
      </p>
    </assemblage>

    <p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-help">Locale</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-icri-correct">ICRI</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-help">Either</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-help">I don't know</xref></p></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs xml:id="Q1-medium-locale-idk">
    <title>I Don't Know - Medium Dataset (After Locale)</title>
    
    <p>
      You hesitate. <q>I<ellipsis/> need to check something.</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      You reopen your analysis.
    </p>

    <p>
      You suddenly notice that you've been looking at overall averages across all three countries.
    </p>

    <p>
      But this farmer is in <alert>Ilam</alert>, and the pattern here is not the same as the overall pattern from your data.
    </p>

    <assemblage>
      <p>
        Hint:
      </p>
      <p>
        Filter the data to Ilam.
      </p>
      <p>
        Then compare yield by variety.
      </p>
    </assemblage>

    <p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-help">Locale</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-icri-correct">ICRI</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-help">Either</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-help">I don't know</xref></p></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs xml:id="Q1-medium-locale-icri">

    <title>Correcting to ICRI - Medium Dataset</title>
    
    <p>
      Yes, ICRI is the right recommendation for Ilam.
    </p>

    <p>
      You've just experienced another instance of <alert>Simpson's Paradox</alert>.
    </p>

    <p>
      In this case:
      <ul>
        <li><p>When you looked at all regions combined, one variety might have appeared better.</p></li>
        <li><p>But when you filtered to Ilam specifically, the pattern reversed.</p></li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <p>
      The key lesson: <alert>Context matters</alert>. Regional, environmental, or social differences can cause aggregate patterns to mislead.
    </p>

    <p>
      Always disaggregate your data when you're giving context-specific advice.
    </p>

    <p>
      Continue to <xref ref="Q2-medium">Question 2</xref>.
    </p>
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs xml:id="Q1-medium-icri-correct">
    <title>ICRI - Ilam (Correct)</title>
    
    <p>
      You smile. <q>For Ilam? Plant the ICRI variety.</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      The farmer nods slowly. <q>That makes sense. It's what many of us have been noticing.</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      You feel relieved -- and slightly humbled.
    </p>

    <p>
      Across the entire dataset, Locale may look stronger on average. But when you break the data down by region, Ilam tells a different story.
    </p>

    <p>
      You've just discovered something important:
    </p>

    <p>
      Overall averages can mislead and the best decision can depend on context.
    </p>

    <p>
      You turn the page in your notebook. This is more complicated than you thought.
    </p>

    <p>
      Continue to <xref ref="Q2-medium">Question 2</xref>.
    </p>
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs xml:id="Q1-medium-icri">
    <title>ICRI - Medium Dataset</title>
    
    <p>
      You say confidently, <q>ICRI.</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      The farmer smiles. <q>Interesting. That matches what some of us have seen.</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      But then he tilts his head. <q>If you're so sure<ellipsis/> tell me this. In which region does ICRI outperform Locale on average?</q> (If there are multiple, give only one)
    </p>

    <p>
      Now it's your turn to think.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Option:</alert>
      <ul>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-locale-correct">Regin</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-anikrub">Anikrub</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-icri-correct">Ilam</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-icri-correct">I don't know</xref></p></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs xml:id="Q1-medium-anikrub">
    <title>Anikrub - Variety</title>
    
    <p>
      You pause.
    </p>

    <p>
      <q>Anikrub?</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      The farmer narrows his eyes.
    </p>

    <p>
      You feel that small tightening in your stomach.
    </p>

    <p>
      You pull out your notebook again.
    </p>

    <p>
      Across the medium dataset, the overall difference between ICRI and Local is<ellipsis/> small.
    </p>

    <p>
      Very small.
    </p>

    <p>
      When you look at Ilam alone, the pattern seems to shift slightly.
    </p>

    <p>
      But is that shift real?
    </p>

    <p>
      Or is it noise?
    </p>

    <p>
      You stare at the numbers. Does knowing this farmer is from Ilam change your answer?
    </p>

    <p>
      The farmer waits.
    </p>

    <p>
      What do you say?
      <ul>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-icri">ICRI</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-locale">Locale</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-help">Either</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-idk">I don't know</xref></p></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs xml:id="Q1-medium-either">
    <title>Either - Medium Dataset</title>
    
    <p>
      You pause.
    </p>

    <p>
      <q>Either one.</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      The farmer narrows his eyes.
    </p>

    <p>
      <q>Either?</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      He shifts his weight. <q>We're in Ilam, you know.</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      You feel that small tightening in your stomach.
    </p>

    <p>
      With a larger dataset, you had thousands of farmers across all three countries. Patterns would be clearer – even if misleading at first glance.
    </p>

    <p>
      But this time, you're working with several hundred farmers. Carefully sampled. Balanced. Manageable.
    </p>

    <p>
      But not enormous.
    </p>

    <p>
      You pull out your notebook again.
    </p>

    <p>
      Across the medium dataset, the overall difference between ICRI and Local is<ellipsis/> small.
    </p>

    <p>
      Very small.
    </p>

    <p>
      When you look at Ilam alone, the pattern seems to shift slightly.
    </p>

    <p>
      But is that shift real?
    </p>

    <p>
      Or is it noise?
    </p>

    <p>
      You stare at the numbers. Does knowing this farmer is from Ilam change your answer?
    </p>

    <p>
      The farmer waits.
    </p>

    <p>
      What do you say?
      <ul>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-icri">ICRI</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-locale">Locale</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-help">Either</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-idk">I don't know</xref></p></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </paragraphs>


  <paragraphs xml:id="Q1-medium-idk">
    <title>I Don't Know - Medium Dataset</title>
    
    <p>
      You stall.
    </p>

    <p>
      <q>Well<ellipsis/> it sure is lovely weather here in Ilam today.</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      The farmer laughs.
    </p>

    <p>
      <q>You statisticians.</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      You realise avoidance won't help.
    </p>

    <assemblage>
      <p>
        <alert>Advice:</alert>
      </p>
      <p>
        Start by comparing average yield by variety.
      </p>
      <p>
        Then break it down by region. This should lead you to your answer
      </p>
    </assemblage>

    <p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-locale">Locale</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-icri-correct">ICRI</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-locale-either">Either</xref></p></li>
        <li><p><xref ref="Q1-medium-help">I don't know</xref></p></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </paragraphs>

  <paragraphs xml:id="Q1-medium-help">
    <title>Help - Medium Dataset</title>
    
    <p>
      Let's walk through this carefully.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Step 1:</alert> Look at overall average yield by variety. You may find that Locale looks better overall.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Step 2:</alert> Now break the data down by region. When you look at Ilam specifically, ICRI outperforms Locale on average.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>What happened?</alert>
    </p>

    <p>
      This is an example of how aggregated data can hide regional differences. The distribution of varieties across regions affects the overall average.
    </p>

    <p>
      Never give advice based only on overall averages when context matters.
    </p>

    <p>
      For Ilam, the correct answer is: <alert>ICRI</alert>
    </p>

    <p>
      Go to <xref ref="Q2-medium">Question 2</xref>.
    </p>
  </paragraphs>

</section>
